<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-881-872  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 881 872.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  Sept 1989 v8 n9 p67(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Stray light in spectrometers: causes and cures. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pierson, Arthur; Goldstein, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The variety of causes of stray light in monochronometers andspectrographs can be reduced or eliminated through baffling,optical and other techniques.andP;  The stray light may be broadband orquasi-monochromatic, but both can adversely impact the opticaldata.andP;  Broadband light can mask data, while monochromatic lightcan look like real emission spectra.andP;  Major causes of stray lightinclude: diffuse reflections of a spectrometer's interior walls,scatter off optical elements including gratings and scratches,scatter off oxidized surfaces, vacuum pump oil in vacuumspectrometers, large-scale defects of optical surfaces, reflectionfrom the backside of exit slits, and re-entry spectra.andP;  Details ofthe causes of, effects of and strategies for reducing oreliminating stray light are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SpectrometryLightingMethodsPerformance ImprovementResearch and DevelopmentOpticsTechnologyOptical Memory.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Schematic diagram of Kohler illumination of a spectrometer.andO;(chart)Schematic diagram of a simple concave monochromator. (chart)An Ebert monochromator suffering from double diffraction. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>